How do we improve code reviews?
___

Yesterday we learned about the top code review complaints #devs have: subjectivity, tone of voice, and process loopholes. Today, I'll tell you what we can do better!
___

On Subjectivity: Let the 🤖 robots take over! They're better at it anyway...what I mean by this is use linters and style analyzers! We shouldn't be fussing over indentation and formatting in a code review, we should be fixing these issues before they even reach the code review stage! And we're much more open to our computer telling us we have these issues (rather than our colleagues!). Lastly, focus on being objective: talk about the code, not the developer.
___

On Tone of Voice: TL;DR Don't be a jerk! But to be a bit more verbose...Suggest, with facts! Reject, with courtesy! Clarify, with an open mind! When you're about to give a suggestion, explain why! If there is truly something wrong with the code, focus on the code and explain why it won't work or why it goes against your team's code standards. If you have questions about how something was implemented, open a discussion with your colleague to learn more, NOT to start an argument on why your implementation would have been better!
___

On Process Loopholes: I can't stress this enough... Enforce the process for EVERYONE! Every dev and every line of code needs to be reviewed. Auto-add reviewers to pull requests! Create a policy that ensures 2 or more approvers are required before merging (even better if you can and are able to require the whole dev team's approval)! Agree beforehand with your team on what the process is 🤝
___

I talk about this in depth in my talk Conducing Humans Code Reviews! Give it a listen if you want to start performing better code reviews ☺️

As you know I am a game developer (unreal engine)...
There’s one rookie mistake I made in the beginning and I am here to stop you from making the same mistake 😇
_
Firstly many noobs confuse Actors with Pawns (that was my mistake). Actors are basically objects that can be placed into a level.
An Actor is your base object for pretty much every game object.
_
And a pawn is an actor that can be controlled by either the player or the games AI.
You’ll want to use Actors for things like tables, doors, lamps, etc.
Meanwhile you’ll want to use Pawns for the monsters, non-playable characters and anything else that is seemingly alive in your game.

Note: each pawn has a controller and vice versa.
